                "citation-title": "The effects of hair-cell polarity on the dynamics of two coupled hair-cell bundles of the inner ear",
                "abstracts": "Â© Published under licence by IOP Publishing Ltd.Hair cells are the sensory receptors of the auditory and vestibular systems. A bundle of cilia situated atop each hair cell, termed the hair-cell bundle, is deflected upon an impinging of a mechanical force. This modulates the open probability of mechanically gated ion channels and subsequently alters the hair cell's membrane potential. Owing to the asymmetry in the hair bundle's geometry, individual hair cells are polarized and display the maximal response to a force applied toward a direction that opens the ion channels. The auditory organs of most vertebrates comprise primarily of hair cells with identical polarity, whereas hair cells of the vestibular organs are organized in two opposing polarities. To understand the advantages of the bi-polarity arrangement of vestibular hair cells, we employed the theoretical framework that describes each hair-cell bundle as an active nonlinear oscillator displaying a Hopf bifurcation. Our results from numerical simulations revealed that coupling of two hair-cell bundles with opposite polarities significantly altered the value of the critical control parameter at a Hopf bifurcation. When driven by a step force, coupled hair-cell bundles with identical polarities displayed a maximal displacement in the direction which closed the ion channels. On the other hand, reversing the polarity of a hair-cell bundle rendered the system sensitive to bi-directional step forces. Lastly, we showed that coupling hair-cell bundles with opposite polarities did not significantly alter the response to sinusoidal forces.",
